<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="316" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1158,1977]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1158,1184]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. In the keys of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundbeck, W." box="[453,649,1159,1185]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" refId="ref14900" refString="Lundbeck, W. (1922) Diptera Danica Part VI Pipunculidae, Phoridae. Wesley, London, 447 pp." type="book" year="1922">Lundbeck (1922)</bibRefCitation>
it runs to Group VII couplet 9 lead 
<specimenCount box="[1074,1129,1159,1185]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" type="generic">
2 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmitz)" baseAuthorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[1098,1129,1159,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="virilis">
<emphasis box="[1098,1129,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
virilis (Schmitz), which is immediately distinguished by its 3 notopleural bristles and some anterodorsal bristles on the outer half of the hind tibia. In the key to the males of the British species (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney R. H. L." box="[715,864,1231,1257]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref14009" refString="Disney R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 10 (8), Royal Entomologicai Society of London, 1 - 155. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631287 X 00115" type="book chapter" year="1989">Disney, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 217 lead 
<specimenCount box="[1171,1222,1231,1257]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" type="generic">
1 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz. It" authorityName="Schmitz. It" box="[1191,1222,1231,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevior">
<emphasis box="[1191,1222,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
brevior Schmitz. It belongs to a complex since revised (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[554,708,1267,1294]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" pagination="41 - 51" refId="ref14155" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2006) Revision of the Palaearctic members of the species complex resembling Megaselia brevior (Schmitz) (Diptera: Phoridae). Fragmenta faunistica 49, 41 - 51. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 00159301 FF 2006.49.1.041" type="journal article" year="2006">Disney, 2006</bibRefCitation>
). In its key it runs to couplet 4 lead 
<specimenCount box="[1104,1156,1267,1293]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" type="generic">
2 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[1125,1156,1267,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevissima">
<emphasis box="[1125,1156,1267,1292]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
brevissima, but its costal index is only 0.30 and it has only 2 axillary bristles. In this complex 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz" authorityName="Schmitz" authorityYear="1935" box="[921,1168,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intersecta">
<emphasis box="[921,1068,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">M. intersecta</emphasis>
Schmitz
</taxonomicName>
is only known from the female, but its costal index is only 0.31–0.32. The male of 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz" authorityName="Schmitz" authorityYear="1957" box="[802,1019,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exsecta">
<emphasis box="[802,920,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">M. exsecta</emphasis>
Schmitz
</taxonomicName>
is too poorly described to covered by the key, but its hairs of the proctiger are longer than those of the cerci and its costal index is only 0.32. Otherwise it fails to run down in keys for the rest of the world’s fauna and subsequent additions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="316" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1158,1977]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1446,1472]" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Frons as 
<figureCitation box="[519,599,1447,1473]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–81" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[263,1319,191,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-32@11.[257,1329,181,1861]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 73–81. Megaselia fayesgadeensis sp. n. male. 73, frons; 74, postpedicels and palps; 75, postpedicels; 76 abdomen; 77, left face of hypopygium; 78, left face of epandrium and hypandrium; 79, right face of hypopygium; 80, front tarsus; 81, hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925235/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
, largely lacking fine microtrichia. Cheek with 4 bristles and jowl with 2 that are longer and more robust. Postpedicels, with numerous SPS vesicles (
<figureCitation box="[953,1036,1482,1509]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–81" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[263,1319,191,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-32@11.[257,1329,181,1861]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 73–81. Megaselia fayesgadeensis sp. n. male. 73, frons; 74, postpedicels and palps; 75, postpedicels; 76 abdomen; 77, left face of hypopygium; 78, left face of epandrium and hypandrium; 79, right face of hypopygium; 80, front tarsus; 81, hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925235/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">Fig. 75</figureCitation>
), and palps 
<figureCitation box="[1170,1252,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–81" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[263,1319,191,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-32@11.[257,1329,181,1861]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 73–81. Megaselia fayesgadeensis sp. n. male. 73, frons; 74, postpedicels and palps; 75, postpedicels; 76 abdomen; 77, left face of hypopygium; 78, left face of epandrium and hypandrium; 79, right face of hypopygium; 80, front tarsus; 81, hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925235/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
, the labella with numerous short spinules below. Thorax brown. Two notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these. Mesopleuron bare. Scutellum with an anterior pair of hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdomen as 
<figureCitation box="[1162,1245,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–81" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[263,1319,191,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-32@11.[257,1329,181,1861]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 73–81. Megaselia fayesgadeensis sp. n. male. 73, frons; 74, postpedicels and palps; 75, postpedicels; 76 abdomen; 77, left face of hypopygium; 78, left face of epandrium and hypandrium; 79, right face of hypopygium; 80, front tarsus; 81, hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925235/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">Fig. 76</figureCitation>
, with small hairs which are not longer at rear of T6, and venter gray with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[1259,1389,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–81" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[263,1319,191,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-32@11.[257,1329,181,1861]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 73–81. Megaselia fayesgadeensis sp. n. male. 73, frons; 74, postpedicels and palps; 75, postpedicels; 76 abdomen; 77, left face of hypopygium; 78, left face of epandrium and hypandrium; 79, right face of hypopygium; 80, front tarsus; 81, hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925235/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">Figs 77–79</figureCitation>
, the hypandrial lobes being very short. Legs yellowish brown. Fore tarsus (
<figureCitation box="[945,1027,1627,1653]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–81" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[263,1319,191,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-32@11.[257,1329,181,1861]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 73–81. Megaselia fayesgadeensis sp. n. male. 73, frons; 74, postpedicels and palps; 75, postpedicels; 76 abdomen; 77, left face of hypopygium; 78, left face of epandrium and hypandrium; 79, right face of hypopygium; 80, front tarsus; 81, hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925235/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">Fig. 80</figureCitation>
) with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.67 times its length. Hairs below basal half of hind femur longer than those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation box="[814,897,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–81" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1884,1908]" captionTargetBox="[263,1319,191,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-32@11.[257,1329,181,1861]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 73–81. Megaselia fayesgadeensis sp. n. male. 73, frons; 74, postpedicels and palps; 75, postpedicels; 76 abdomen; 77, left face of hypopygium; 78, left face of epandrium and hypandrium; 79, right face of hypopygium; 80, front tarsus; 81, hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925235/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="316">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
). Hind tibia with about two dozen differentiated posterodorsal hairs that are more robust on outer two thirds, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (fig 238) about 
<quantity box="[500,601,1771,1797]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.43" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" unit="mm" value="1.43">1.43 mm</quantity>
m long. Costal index about 0.37. Costal ratios 5: 1.1: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[268,368,1807,1833]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" unit="mm" value="0.07">0.07 mm</quantity>
long. Vein 3 hair 
<quantity box="[568,668,1807,1833]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" unit="mm" value="0.01">0.01 mm</quantity>
long. With 3 axillary bristles, the outermost being 
<quantity box="[1238,1338,1807,1833]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="10" pageNumber="316" unit="mm" value="0.13">0.13 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere knob yellow
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
